Φ(Taxonomy Values Love) = σ(value_types|love_forms) ∘ ρ(ethical_values|relational_love_expressions) ∘ λ(isolated_categories|integrated_taxonomy) ∘ β(surface_attraction|deepening_unconditional_love) ∘ δγ(value_love_mapping_cycling|relationship_assessment_iteration) ∘ μ(categorical_taxonomy_framework|value_love_interrelation_architecture) + ε | :integrated_value_love_coherence

## Operator Breakdown

- **σ (Air/Aerunik — Distinction)**: value_types|love_forms — The foundational distinction between values (ethical, economic, social, organisational, personal) as systems of principle and love forms (empathy, obsession, interest, admiration, true love) as relational orientations; the taxonomy treats these as distinct categorical domains that nevertheless share deep structural interconnections, where each form of love corresponds to and is shaped by underlying value commitments
- **ρ (Water/Sentaria — Relation)**: ethical_values|relational_love_expressions — The relational mapping between value categories and love forms, revealing systematic correspondences: empathy aligns with ethical values of caring and compassion, admiration connects with social values of generosity, true love resonates with personal values of selflessness, obsession links to economic values of status, and interest relates to organisational values of efficiency; these correspondences reveal that love is never value-neutral but always structured by the values it expresses
- **λ (Fire/Jvalion — Transformation)**: isolated_categories|integrated_taxonomy — The transformative synthesis of what are typically treated as isolated categories (values listed separately from love) into an integrated taxonomy that reveals their structural interconnections; this catalytic integration enables recognition that the quality of love in any relationship is fundamentally determined by the values underlying it
- **β (Wood/Arboriel — Growth)**: surface_attraction|deepening_unconditional_love — The developmental trajectory from surface-level attraction (obsession with looks, interest in money) toward deepening unconditional love (being unsure why you love someone); this growth path moves from love grounded in economic and status-based values toward love that transcends specific attributes and resonates with personal values of selflessness and tolerance
- **δγ (Earth/Humavita — Cycling)**: value_love_mapping_cycling|relationship_assessment_iteration — The cycling through value-love mappings and iterative assessment of relationships through value analysis and value engineering; relationships are continuously evaluated and modified through the lens of value creation — sustainable value, shared value, value engineering, and value analysis — creating an iterative process of relational refinement
- **μ (Metal/Ferrosid — Structure)**: categorical_taxonomy_framework|value_love_interrelation_architecture — The dominant structural element — the categorical taxonomy itself as an organizational framework that systematically maps five value types against five love forms, revealing the architecture of their interrelation; this framework provides a comprehensive structure for understanding how values and love mutually constitute and reinforce each other in relational contexts

## Z-State

:integrated_value_love_coherence — Values and love forms are not separate domains but structurally interconnected systems where ethical values (honesty, compassion, fidelity) correspond to empathetic and admiring love, economic values align with interest-based love, and true unconditional love resonates with personal values of selflessness and tolerance. The Z-state is achieved when the taxonomy reveals that the quality of love in relationships is fundamentally shaped by the values underlying it, and that value creation in relationships (sustainable, shared, engineered) depends on the conscious alignment of value systems with love expressions. This integrated understanding enables both diagnostic assessment of relationships and intentional cultivation of deeper relational bonds through value alignment.

